1. First, create a container div and give it a display:flex property. This will start applying flexbox to the container.
```css
.container {
  display: flex;
}
```
2. Add the divs you want to align as children of the container div. Give them a class or id for easy targeting later.
```html
<div class="container">
  <div class="div1"></div>
  <div class="div2"></div>
  <div class="div3"></div>
</div>
```
3. To align the divs to the right, you can use the justify-content:flex-end property on the container div. This will position the divs from right to left in the container.
```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: flex-end;
}
```
4. You can also adjust the spacing between the divs by using the flex-basis property. This will give each div a fixed amount of space based on its content and adjust it to fill the remaining space in the container if needed.
```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: flex-end;
}

.div1, .div2, .div3 {
  flex-basis: 100%; /* This will give each div 100% of the available space */
}
```
That's it! You should now have a row of divs aligned to the right using flex in CSS.
